  <!-- SECTION 2: Types of Copper Ore — neutral-50 bg -->
  <section class="bg-neutral-50 py-24">
    <div class="container mx-auto px-8 max-w-7xl">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4 text-center">Types of Copper Ore</h2>
        <p class="text-lg text-neutral-700 mb-10 text-center max-w-5xl mx-auto">
          There are three main types of copper ore — <strong>sulfide</strong>, <strong>oxide</strong>, and <strong>carbonate</strong> — 
          each formed under different geological conditions and requiring different extraction methods.
        </p>
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6">

        <!-- Sulfide -->
        <div class="bg-white rounded-lg overflow-hidden border border-neutral-200">
          <img 
            src="/materials/copper/sulfide-ore.jpg" 
            alt="Sulfide copper ore"
            class="w-full h-48 object-cover"
          />
          <div class="p-6">
            <p class="font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Sulfide Copper Ores</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600 mb-4">
              Copper combined with sulfur, found deep underground and formed by hydrothermal processes.
            </p>
            <div class="mb-3">
              <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-1">Examples</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">Chalcopyrite, Bornite, Chalcocite</p>
            </div>
            <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">
              Extracted mainly through smelting and flotation (pyrometallurgical processing).
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Oxide — FEATURED -->
        <div class="bg-white rounded-lg overflow-hidden border-2 border-accent-500 shadow-md relative">
          <div class="absolute top-3 right-3 bg-accent-500 text-white px-3 py-1 text-xs font-bold rounded-full z-10">
            OUR SPECIALTY
          </div>
          <img 
            src="/materials/copper/oxide-ore.jpg" 
            alt="Oxide copper ore"
            class="w-full h-48 object-cover"
          />
          <div class="p-6">
            <p class="font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Oxide Copper Ores</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600 mb-4">
              Copper combined with oxygen, typically found near the Earth's surface through the weathering of sulfide ores.
            </p>
            <div class="mb-3">
              <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-1">Examples</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">Cuprite, Tenorite</p>
            </div>
            <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">
              Processed using leaching and electrolysis (hydrometallurgical processing).
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Carbonate -->
        <div class="bg-white rounded-lg overflow-hidden border border-neutral-200">
          <img 
            src="/materials/copper/carbonate-ore.jpg" 
            alt="Carbonate copper ore"
            class="w-full h-48 object-cover"
          />
          <div class="p-6">
            <p class="font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Carbonate Copper Ores</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600 mb-4">
              Copper combined with carbonate ions, found in the oxidation zones of copper deposits.
            </p>
            <div class="mb-3">
              <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-1">Examples</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">Malachite, Azurite</p>
            </div>
            <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">
              Often processed by leaching, and in some cases directly smelted.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- SECTION 3: Advantages — white bg -->
  <section class="bg-white py-16">
    <div class="container mx-auto px-8 max-w-5xl">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Advantages of Copper Oxide Ores</h2>
      <p class="text-lg text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-10">
        While all copper ores have industrial value, we've focused on oxide ores for compelling operational, 
        environmental, and quality reasons.
      </p>

      <ul class="space-y-5">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
          <Leaf class="w-5 h-5 text-accent-600 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5" />
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm leading-relaxed">
            <strong>Sustainable Processing: </strong>Oxide ores respond exceptionally well to hydrometallurgical methods — 
            leaching and electrolysis — which consume significantly less energy than traditional smelting and produce 
            minimal emissions compared to sulfide ore processing.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
          <Mountain class="w-5 h-5 text-accent-600 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5" />
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm leading-relaxed">
            <strong>Accessibility & Efficiency: </strong>Located near the Earth's surface, oxide ores enable efficient 
            extraction with reduced environmental disturbance and lower operational costs compared to deep underground mining.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
          <Atom class="w-5 h-5 text-accent-600 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5" />
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm leading-relaxed">
            <strong>High-Purity Output: </strong>Our leaching and electrowinning process delivers 99.99% pure copper 
            cathodes, meeting the most demanding industry specifications without the sulfur dioxide emissions associated 
            with smelting.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
          <TrendingUp class="w-5 h-5 text-accent-600 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5" />
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm leading-relaxed">
            <strong>Decades of Expertise: </strong>Our geological understanding of oxide ore formation, combined with 
            optimized processing technology, positions us as leaders in oxide copper extraction and refinement.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- SECTION 4: Extraction & Processing — dark bg -->
  <section class="bg-primary-500 py-16">
    <div class="container mx-auto px-8 max-w-5xl">
      <p class="text-accent-400 font-semibold text-lg mb-4">PROCESS</p>
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold !text-white mb-4">Extraction & Processing</h2>
      <p class="text-neutral-400 text-lg mb-12">
        Our proven hydrometallurgical process, optimized for maximum copper recovery and purity.
      </p>

      <div class="space-y-0">

        <!-- Step 1 -->
        <div class="flex items-start gap-6 ">
          <div class="flex flex-col items-center flex-shrink-0 ">
            <div class="w-9 h-9 bg-accent-500 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-sm z-10">
              1
            </div>
            <div class="w-px h-full min-h-[80px] bg-neutral-700 mt-1"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="pb-10 text-white ">
            <h4 class="font-bold !text-white mb-2">Extraction & Preparation</h4>
            <p class="text-neutral-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
              Ore is carefully extracted from near-surface deposits using modern mining techniques, then crushed and sized 
              to optimal particle dimensions — maximizing surface area for efficient chemical processing.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Step 2 -->
        <div class="flex items-start gap-6">
          <div class="flex flex-col items-center flex-shrink-0">
            <div class="w-9 h-9 bg-accent-500 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-sm z-10">
              2
            </div>
            <div class="w-px h-full min-h-[80px] bg-neutral-700 mt-1"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="pb-10">
            <h4 class="font-bold !text-white mb-2">Heap Leaching</h4>
            <p class="text-neutral-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
              Crushed ore is placed in engineered heap structures on impermeable liners, then irrigated with dilute sulfuric 
              acid. The acid dissolves copper from the ore, creating a copper-rich solution known as pregnant leach solution (PLS).
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Step 3 -->
        <div class="flex items-start gap-6">
          <div class="flex flex-col items-center flex-shrink-0">
            <div class="w-9 h-9 bg-accent-500 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-sm z-10">
              3
            </div>
            <div class="w-px h-full min-h-[80px] bg-neutral-700 mt-1"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="pb-10">
            <h4 class="font-bold !text-white mb-2">Solvent Extraction (SX)</h4>
            <p class="text-neutral-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
              The PLS undergoes solvent extraction to concentrate copper and remove impurities. Organic solvents selectively 
              bind copper, producing a high-grade copper electrolyte solution while rejecting unwanted elements.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Step 4 - no line after last -->
        <div class="flex items-start gap-6">
          <div class="flex-shrink-0">
            <div class="w-9 h-9 bg-accent-500 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-sm">
              4
            </div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h4 class="font-bold !text-white mb-2">Electrowinning (EW)</h4>
            <p class="text-neutral-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
              The concentrated copper solution flows through electrowinning cells where electrical current plates pure copper 
              onto cathode starter sheets — yielding 99.99% pure copper cathodes ready for industrial use without further refining.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- SECTION 5: Key Properties — neutral-50 bg -->
   <ImageTextSection 
    imageSrc="/materials/copper/copper-gold-upclose.JPG"
    imageAlt="Close-up of copper ore"
    imagePosition="left"
    background="grey"
    heading="Key Properties"
  >
  <PropertyList 
      properties={[
        'High copper grades ensuring economically viable extraction and processing',
        'Near-surface accessibility enabling efficient extraction with minimal environmental disturbance',
        'Optimal processing response achieving 80-90% copper recovery rates',
        'Consistent quality through comprehensive geological characterization and grade control',
        'Sustainable extraction with significantly lower carbon footprint than sulfide ore processing',
        'Low impurity levels naturally present in oxide ores, producing cleaner final copper products'
        ]}
        columns={1}
    /> 
   </ImageTextSection>
  

  <!-- SECTION 6: Applications — white bg -->
  <section class="bg-white py-16">
    <div class="container mx-auto px-8 max-w-5xl">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Applications</h2>
      <p class="text-lg text-neutral-700 mb-8">
        The high-purity copper derived from our oxide ores serves as the foundation for countless essential applications 
        across modern industry:
      </p>

      <div class="space-y-5">

        <div class="border-l-4 border-accent-500 bg-neutral-50 pl-5 py-2">
          <h4 class="font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-1">Electrical & Power</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm leading-relaxed">
            Copper's superior conductivity makes it the global standard for building wiring, power grid infrastructure, 
            high-voltage transmission lines, substations, and electric motors and generators powering everything from 
            industrial machinery to household appliances.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="border-l-4 border-accent-500 bg-neutral-50 pl-5 py-2">
          <h4 class="font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-1">Construction & Infrastructure</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm leading-relaxed">
            Copper pipes deliver potable water safely with inherent antimicrobial properties that inhibit bacterial growth. 
            Architectural copper provides weather resistance and durability exceeding 100 years, while HVAC systems rely on 
            copper's thermal conductivity for efficient climate control.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="border-l-4 border-accent-500 bg-neutral-50 pl-5 py-2">
          <h4 class="font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-1">Renewable Energy</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm leading-relaxed">
            Solar photovoltaic systems and thermal installations depend on copper for electrical connections and heat transfer. 
            Wind turbines contain substantial copper in generators (up to 1 ton per MW), and battery energy storage systems 
            rely on copper for efficient power management.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="border-l-4 border-accent-500 bg-neutral-50 pl-5 py-2">
          <h4 class="font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-1">Electronics & Transportation</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm leading-relaxed">
            Copper forms the conductive pathways in printed circuit boards, semiconductors, and consumer electronics. 
            Modern vehicles contain 20-50 kg of copper in wiring and motors, while electric vehicles require 2-4 times 
            more copper than conventional vehicles for traction motors, battery systems, and charging infrastructure.
          </p>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

